const faqs = [
  { q: "Who owns Wascomat and what's the Electrolux Professional connection?", a: "Wascomat is the US-market commercial laundry brand within the Electrolux Professional family. The chassis engineering originates from Electrolux Professional Laundry (Swedish heritage; Ljungby Sweden manufacturing), distributed and serviced in the US under the Wascomat badge. The relationship traces back decades through Laundrylux, the long-time US distributor for Wascomat and Electrolux Professional Laundry products. This is why you'll hear Wascomat, Electrolux Professional Laundry, and Laundrylux used somewhat interchangeably at LA laundromats — they refer to overlapping corners of the same distribution + service ecosystem. The operational takeaway: Wascomat parts run through the Electrolux Professional + Laundrylux distribution network, not through the Alliance (Speed Queen/UniMac/Huebsch) or Dexter channels. Our service coordinates parts through the correct Wascomat distributor based on model and serial." },
  { q: "Which Wascomat models do you see in LA laundromats?", a: "The Crossover series dominates current Wascomat installs — Crossover 2.0 washers and dryers in 20, 30, 40, 60, 80, 100 lb capacities, with coin-op, card-ready, and OPL-programmable variants. The Emerald series (Emerald 20, 30, 40 lb) handles the laundromat-focused mid-capacity segment with Wascomat's EnvoyUltra control platform. Gen.6 is the older generation still running at long-established laundromats — the installed base for Gen.6 in LA laundromats is real even though new Wascomat orders default to Crossover 2.0 now. Wascomat TD single-pocket dryers + DS stack configurations cover the dryer side. Select Wascomat laundromats in Koreatown + Hollywood + East LA run mixed Crossover + Emerald fleets we service as one account." },
  { q: "Wascomat vs Speed Queen — how do LA laundromat operators pick?", a: "Brand preference at the LA laundromat level is usually legacy-driven and operator-specific rather than sharp performance differentiation. Speed Queen (Alliance Laundry Systems, Ripon WI, ESOP since 2018) runs the larger overall US install base and dominates default new-laundromat specifications. Wascomat (Electrolux Professional Laundry, Swedish design heritage) has a loyal segment of the LA market — operators who've specified Wascomat historically often stay on Wascomat through refit cycles. The European engineering heritage shows up in control-platform design (EnvoyUltra vs Alliance's Quantum), in some cycle-programming conventions, and in parts-supply channel specifics. Neither brand dominates LA universally; both show up across Koreatown, East LA, Hollywood, Pico-Union, and South LA laundromats. Our service covers both without preference — call us with model number and we route parts correctly." },
  { q: "Do you service Wascomat at LA hotel and institutional OPL?", a: "Yes. Wascomat + Electrolux Professional Laundry OPL specification shows up at certain LA hotels (particularly properties with European-parent ownership groups that default-spec Electrolux Professional globally), plus institutional installs where the original property-management spec was Electrolux Professional. Typical Wascomat OPL service: door gasket replacements on high-cycle front-loads; inverter drive diagnostics after LA brownouts; EnvoyUltra control-platform firmware + programming questions when OPL cycles need adjustment for specific linen types or chemical-injection sequences; and drain-valve or drain-pump work on Crossover units running high-alkaline or softener-heavy water chemistries. Same-day dispatch on OPL emergencies applies." },
  { q: "Wascomat EnvoyUltra control fault — what's the diagnostic sequence?", a: "EnvoyUltra is the Wascomat programmable control platform on Crossover and Emerald series. After power events or firmware cycles, the platform can enter a fault state that locks out cycle start or displays a communication error with the washer's inverter drive or motor control board. Diagnostic sequence: read the fault code from the EnvoyUltra display; cycle the main disconnect for 60 seconds to fully reset the control board and VFD; verify the sub-menu programming wasn't corrupted by the power event (reload factory defaults if needed, then re-enter operator-specific cycle settings); check the drive-to-control communication wiring for loose terminals; test the motor for winding or bearing issues if fault persists. Most EnvoyUltra fault calls resolve at reset + programming reload; actual control board replacement is needed in roughly 8-12% of cases and runs $700-$1,200 installed." }
];

