  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>What breaks — EnvoyUltra controls, door gaskets, drain systems</h2>
    <p>Wascomat failure mix differs slightly from Speed Queen + Dexter because of the European control platform and the specific drive + drain architecture on Crossover units.</p>
    <p><b>EnvoyUltra control faults</b> concentrate on Crossover 2.0 and Emerald series. After LA power events (brownouts + hard shutoffs + thunderstorm cycles), the platform can enter a fault state locking out cycle start or showing a drive-communication error. Diagnostic: read the fault code, cycle the main disconnect for 60 seconds for full reset, verify sub-menu programming wasn't corrupted (factory reset + re-enter operator cycle settings if needed), check drive-to-control wiring, test motor. Most faults resolve at reset + programming reload; control-board replacement needed in ~8-12% of fault cases.</p>
    <p><b>Door gasket deformation</b> on high-cycle Crossover front-loads is the routine consumable. At 20,000+ cycles, gaskets compress and deform; early signs are door-close resistance changes and slow leaks at the bottom frame during spin. Replacement runs $220-$380 typical. Some Emerald and Gen.6 legacy gaskets carry longer lead times through the Laundrylux parts channel.</p>
    <p><b>Drain system issues</b> on Crossover specifically — the drain valve architecture on Crossover uses a different valve topology than some Alliance + Dexter front-loads, and drain-valve failures present differently. Drain-valve service runs $260-$440; drain pump replacements separately $260-$440. LA hard-water scale accumulation affects inlet valve longevity on Crossover comparable to other brands.</p>
  </div></section>

